<hl>
<seg id=1> Thailand Welcomes Surrender Of Khieu Samphan </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Reported by Bangkok correspondent Liu Zhenting </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The Thai government welcomed the surrender to authorities in Phnom Penh of two important members of the Khmer Rouge, Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, yesterday. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Foreign Affairs spokesperson Gusa said at the press conference, "The surrender of these two is an example of democracy in Cambodia and an important event in the effort to bring to an end internal conflict, it will bring peace to Cambodia, and make the region stable." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Gusa said Thailand definitely will not support any activity by any Cambodian side that uses Thailand to overthrow a neighboring country. </seg>
<seg id=6> As soon as it is discovered that armed foreigners are using Thai territory for their activity, Thailand will disarm them and bring them to account under the law. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> He also said that Thailand signed a criminal extradition treaty with Hun Sen's government in May of this year. With this Thailand can lawfully handover wanted Cambodians to authorities in Phnom Penh. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Based on another report revealed by persons in Phnom Penh, Thai foreign affairs minister Sulin has invited Cambodian foreign affairs minister He Nanhong to Bangkok for a visit at the beginning of next year to discuss ensuring peace along the border and the thousands of Cambodian refugees stranded in Thailand. They will also consider reinstating the offer of human resources training aid to Cambodia. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Cambodia has been accepted as the tenth member country of ASEAN. The ASEAN foreign minister has been authorized to prepare an official welcoming ceremony for Cambodia at the summit meeting in Hanoi in the middle of this month. </seg>
</p>
